inputs.question: any closed taxiways in Sydney my man?

outputs.answer: Yes, there are closed taxiways in Sydney. According to the NOTAMs, TWY B and TWY C between TWY G and TWY B10 are closed, as well as TWY K and TWY B8. Additionally, TWY A between RWY 07/25 and TWY L is closed for aircraft with a maximum wing span of 36 meters. These closures are in effect from 2311051200 to 2312071900, daily from Sunday to Thursday. The Method of Working Plan 23/002 provides more details on these closures.

inputs.question: I got an A320 u think I'd be okay for TWY L restriuctions?

outputs.answer: According to the NOTAMs, TWY L is closed for aircraft with a maximum wing span of 36 meters. Since the A320 has a wingspan of approximately 34 meters, it should be within the allowed limit and you should be okay to use TWY L. However, it is always recommended to double-check with the airport authorities or consult the Method of Working Plan 23/002 for more specific information regarding the restrictions and limitations.

inputs.question: Any drone ops?

outputs.answer: Yes, there are drone operations mentioned in the NOTAMs. According to the NOTAM F3797/23, unmanned aircraft (multicopter below 25kg) operations will take place within a 50-meter radius of position 335236.93S 1510931.32E, bearing 334 degrees magnetic, 4.2 nautical miles from the aerodrome reference point (ARP). The operators will maintain communication with the tower frequency 120.5 or 124.7. These operations are authorized from the surface to a maximum altitude of 132 feet above ground level (AGL). The NOTAM provides the contact telephone number for the operators as 0429 597 269.

inputs.question: Any like small UA ops anywhere

outputs.answer: Yes, there are small unmanned aircraft (UA) operations mentioned in the NOTAMs. According to NOTAM F3893/23, UA (multicopter below 7kg) operations will take place within 250 meters on either side of a line between positions 335534S 1511310E bearing 047 degrees magnetic, 2.4 nautical miles from the aerodrome reference point (ARP), and position 335622S 1511202E bearing 058 degrees magnetic, 1.2 nautical miles from the ARP. These operations will be monitored on tower frequency 120.5 or 124.7, and the operators can be contacted at 0432 397 713. The maximum altitude for these operations is 98 feet above ground level (AGL).

inputs.question: any closed taxiways in Sydney my man?

outputs.answer: Yes, there are closed taxiways in Sydney. According to the NOTAMs, TWY B and TWY C between TWY G and TWY B10 are closed, as well as TWY K and TWY B8. Additionally, TWY A between RWY 07/25 and TWY L is closed for aircraft with a maximum wing span of 36 meters. These closures are in effect from 2311051200 to 2312071900, daily from Sunday to Thursday. The Method of Working Plan 23/002 provides more details on these closures.

inputs.question: I got an A320 u think I'd be okay for TWY L restriuctions?

outputs.answer: According to the NOTAMs, TWY L is closed for aircraft with a maximum wing span of 36 meters. However, it is always recommended to double-check with the airport authorities or consult the Method of Working Plan 23/002 for more specific information regarding the restrictions and limitations.

inputs.question: Any drone ops?

outputs.answer: Yes, there are drone operations mentioned in the NOTAMs. According to the NOTAM F3797/23, unmanned aircraft (multicopter below 25kg) operations will take place within a 50-meter radius of position 335236.93S 1510931.32E, bearing 334 degrees magnetic, 4.2 nautical miles from the aerodrome reference point (ARP). The operators will maintain communication with the tower frequency 120.5 or 124.7. These operations are authorized from the surface to a maximum altitude of 132 feet above ground level (AGL). The NOTAM provides the contact telephone number for the operators as 0429 597 269.

inputs.question: Any like small UA ops anywhere

outputs.answer: Yes, there are small unmanned aircraft (UA) operations mentioned in the NOTAMs. According to NOTAM F3893/23, UA (multicopter below 7kg) operations will take place within 250 meters on either side of a line between positions 335534S 1511310E bearing 047 degrees magnetic, 2.4 nautical miles from the aerodrome reference point (ARP), and position 335622S 1511202E bearing 058 degrees magnetic, 1.2 nautical miles from the ARP. These operations will be monitored on tower frequency 120.5 or 124.7, and the operators can be contacted at 0432 397 713. The maximum altitude for these operations is 98 feet above ground level (AGL).
